definitions: make a sharp hard sound when two hard objects hit each other repeatedly
examples: Her high heels clacked loudly on the marble floor
The train wheels clacked rhythmically along the metal tracks

definitions: suddenly refuse to talk or give information about something when asked
examples: The witness clammed up when asked about the incident
She always clams up when people ask personal questions

definitions: shout loudly and insistently as a group to demand or protest something
examples: The crowd clamored for justice outside the courthouse building
Reporters clamored for answers during the press conference yesterday

definitions: hold or press things tightly together using force or a special tool
impose strict controls or restrictions on activities or behavior
examples: The carpenter clamped the wood pieces before gluing them
She clamped her hand over her mouth to stop laughing
The government clamped down on illegal street vendors last month
The school clamped new restrictions on student cell phone use

definitions: make a loud dull metallic sound when heavy metal objects hit each other
examples: The prisoner's chains clanked as he walked down the hallway
Old pipes clank loudly when the heating system turns on

definitions: bring your hands together quickly and repeatedly to make noise showing approval
put or place something somewhere quickly and forcefully
examples: The audience clapped enthusiastically after the amazing performance ended
Everyone clapped when she announced her engagement at dinner
He clapped his hat on his head and rushed outside
She clapped the book shut when her mother entered

definitions: come into conflict or violent disagreement with opposing ideas or people
look bad together because colors or styles do not match
examples: The two political parties clashed over the new tax policy
Protesters clashed with police during the demonstration last night
That orange shirt clashes terribly with your green pants
Her modern furniture clashes with the vintage wallpaper design

definitions: hold someone or something tightly with your hands or arms
examples: She clasped her mother's hand during the scary movie
The child clasped the teddy bear tightly while sleeping

definitions: scratch or tear at something using fingernails or sharp curved nails
examples: The cat clawed at the furniture despite having a scratching post
She clawed her way through the thick jungle undergrowth

definitions: clean something thoroughly to remove dirt or harmful substances completely
examples: She cleanses her face every night with gentle soap
The ritual was meant to cleanse their souls of guilt

definitions: split or divide something by cutting with a sharp heavy tool
remain very close or loyal to someone or something
examples: The lumberjack cleaved the log with one powerful swing
Lightning cleaved the old oak tree right down the middle
Young children cleave to their parents in unfamiliar situations
She cleaved to her principles despite facing harsh criticism

definitions: reach the most intense or important point in a series of events
examples: The movie climaxes with an unexpected plot twist ending
The celebration climaxed with a spectacular fireworks display overhead

definitions: settle or win something decisively after competition or negotiation
hold someone tightly in a close embrace or wrestling position
examples: She clinched the championship with a brilliant final performance
They clinched the business deal after weeks of negotiations
The boxers clinched in the middle of the ring
The couple clinched passionately at the train station farewell

definitions: hold on tightly to someone or something refusing to let go
examples: The baby monkey clings to its mother's fur constantly
Wet clothes cling uncomfortably to your skin after swimming

definitions: hide or disguise something by covering it or keeping it secret
examples: The company cloaked its true intentions behind charitable donations
Fog cloaked the mountain peaks early in the morning

definitions: block a pipe or passage so that liquids cannot flow through
examples: Hair and soap often clog bathroom drains over time
Too many cars clogged the narrow streets during rush hour

definitions: keep someone away from the outside world in a quiet protected place
examples: The monks cloistered themselves in the monastery for prayer
She cloistered herself in her room to finish the novel

definitions: create an exact genetic copy of a plant animal or other organism
examples: Scientists successfully cloned a sheep named Dolly in 1996
The company cloned their most popular software for distribution

definitions: bring something to an end or close something permanently
examples: The factory will closure next month due to financial losses
They need to closure old accounts before opening new ones

definitions: form into a thick mass when blood or liquid becomes partially solid
examples: Blood clots quickly when exposed to air outside the body
The cream clotted because it was left out too long

definitions: provide someone with clothes or dress them in particular garments
examples: Parents must clothe their children appropriately for cold weather
The charity helps clothe homeless people during winter months

definitions: hit someone or something hard with your hand or an object
examples: He clouted the ball over the fence with his bat
She clouted him on the head for his rude comment

definitions: behave in a silly or funny way to make people laugh
examples: He always clowns around during class to get attention
Stop clowning and help me with this serious problem

definitions: walk with heavy noisy steps especially in boots
form into or gather in a tight group or mass
examples: The children clumped upstairs in their muddy rain boots
We could hear him clumping around in the apartment above
The sheep clumped together for warmth during the storm
Wet flour tends to clump when you add water slowly

definitions: grab or hold something tightly especially when afraid or in danger
examples: She clutched her purse tightly in the crowded subway
The child clutched his mother's hand during the thunderstorm

definitions: fill a space with too many things in an untidy disorganized way
examples: Old newspapers cluttered the garage floor for many years
Don't clutter your desk with unnecessary items and papers

definitions: come together gradually to form one larger group or whole unit
examples: The small groups coalesced into one powerful political movement
Water droplets coalesce to form larger drops on the window

definitions: persuade someone gently and patiently to do something they are reluctant about
examples: She coaxed the frightened kitten out from under the bed
He coaxed his grandmother into sharing her secret recipe

definitions: put something together quickly and roughly using whatever materials are available
examples: They cobbled together a makeshift shelter from old boards
She cobbled up a quick meal from leftovers in the fridge

definitions: tilt or turn something especially your head to one side
examples: The dog cocked its head when it heard the strange noise
He cocked his hat at a jaunty angle before leaving

definitions: wrap someone or something completely in soft material for protection or comfort
examples: She cocooned herself in warm blankets during the blizzard
The parents cocooned their child from all harsh realities

definitions: arrange laws or rules into an organized system or code
examples: The government codified all tax regulations into one comprehensive document
They need to codify company policies for new employee training

definitions: force someone to do something by using threats or pressure
examples: The gang coerced local businesses into paying protection money
She was coerced into signing the contract against her will

definitions: exist together at the same time or place without conflict
examples: Different religions coexist peacefully in this diverse neighborhood community
Modern buildings coexist with historic architecture in the city center

definitions: wind something into a series of loops or circles
examples: The sailor coiled the rope neatly on the ship's deck
The snake coiled itself around the tree branch slowly

definitions: happen at the same time or occupy the same place by chance
examples: Her birthday coincides with the spring festival this year
Our vacation plans coincide perfectly with the school holidays

definitions: work together with others on a project or activity to achieve something
examples: The two companies collaborated on developing the new software
Artists often collaborate to create more innovative works together

definitions: crash into each other with force while moving in different directions
examples: Two cars collided at the intersection during rush hour
The football players collided hard in the middle of the field

definitions: take control of a country or area and send people to live there
examples: European powers colonised many African countries in the nineteenth century
Bacteria quickly colonise any warm moist surface in kitchens

definitions: take control of a country or area and send people to live there
examples: Spain colonized much of South America in the sixteenth century
These plants will colonize any empty space in your garden

definitions: add color to something using paint dye or other coloring materials
influence someone's opinion or judgment in an unfair way
examples: Children love to colour pictures in their coloring books
She decided to colour her hair red for the summer
Don't let emotions colour your judgment about this important decision
His past experiences clearly colour his views on politics

definitions: arrange or clean hair using a comb tool with teeth
search through an area very carefully and thoroughly
examples: She combs her long hair every morning before school
He combed his beard to make it look neat
Police combed the forest looking for the missing child
We combed through old records to find the information

definitions: remember and show respect for someone or something important with a special ceremony or action
examples: The monument commemorates soldiers who died in the war
Every year we commemorate the founding of our nation

definitions: begin something especially something formal or important
examples: The ceremony will commence at exactly ten o'clock tomorrow morning
She commenced her new job at the law firm yesterday

definitions: praise someone formally or officially for something they have done well
examples: The mayor commended the firefighters for their brave rescue efforts
Her boss commended her excellent work on the difficult project

definitions: develop something to make money from it as a business rather than other purposes
examples: They commercialized their grandmother's cookie recipe into a bakery business
Critics say the festival has become too commercialized over time

definitions: share your thoughts and feelings deeply with someone or something spiritual
examples: She likes to commune with nature during her morning walks
The mystic claimed to commune with spirits from ancient times

definitions: travel regularly between home and work or school
reduce a punishment especially changing a death sentence to life imprisonment
examples: She commutes two hours daily to her office downtown
Many workers commute by train to avoid traffic congestion
The governor commuted the prisoner's death sentence to life imprisonment
The judge commuted her fine to community service hours

definitions: press something together to make it smaller and take up less space
examples: The machine compacts trash into small cubes for disposal
Fresh snow compacts when you walk on it repeatedly
